<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Inclusion Scotland</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:16pt; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">by Inclusion Scotland</span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Under Occupation Penalty or “Bedroom Tax” has already resulted in disproportionately high levels of rent arrears being incurred by RSLs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and Local Authorities in Scotland. This is only likely to increase as time goes by.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given the very high level of arrears already incurred early estimates by Scottish Government of the likely level of rent arrears, and thus potential numbers who would subs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">equently be evicted may have been over-optimistic. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The cumulative impact of welfare benefit cuts will severely reduce the financial resilience of households containing disabled people making them less likely to be able to maintain rent payments if they i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncur an Under Occupation Penalty.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disabled tenants in their late 40s through to late 50s are the most likely to be impacted by several different benefit cuts.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Current exemptions to the Under Occupation Penalty are neither consistent with earlier court de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cisions nor with the hu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">man rights of disable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Recent Lower Tier Tribunal decisions place further question marks over the current exemptions regime.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disabled people are being unfairly denied access to Discretionary Housing Payments, intended to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assist them in mitigating the impact of the Under Occupation Penalty, on the basis of their receipt of DLA or PIP.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.75pt; text-indent:-39.75pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.75pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion Scotland (IS) is a national network of disabled peoples' organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and individual disabled people funded by the Scottish Government. Inclusion Scotland’s main aim is to draw attention to the physical, social, economic, cultural and attitudinal barriers that affect disabled people’s everyday lives in Scotland.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland’s membership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">collectively represents several thousand disabled people from throughout Scotland.  Welfare Reforms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and in particular changes to Housing Support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nstitute the issue of greatest concern to our members.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.75pt; text-indent:-39.75pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Under-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">occupancy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">penalty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> - “Bedroom Tax”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scottish Government estimates that 95,000 Scottish households will be affected by the Bedroom Tax in the first year. In Scotland 79% of the households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">expected to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">affected (76,000) contain a disabled person</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. They will lose an average of £13 pw in housing benefit. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although tenants are being penalised for under-occupying, there is a chronic shortage of 1-bedroom properties.  North Lanarkshire Council, the largest social landlord in Scotland, has 33,000 prope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rties but as of July only 26 of those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">properties </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">currently available were single bedroom properties.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the end of May 2013</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a Scottish Government survey of local authorities found that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there were an estimated 82,500 households in Scotland incurring a red</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uction in their housing benefit because they were assessed as under occupying their property.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of these households:</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around 68,500 were under-occupying by one bedroom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (i.e. 14% penalty)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around 14,000 were under-occupying by two or more bedrooms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (25% penalty)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around 47,500 were local authority tenants.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around 35,000 were housing association tenants.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A research study </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">carried out by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">False Economy on behalf of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> TUC </span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">via Freedom of Information requests </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">found that Scottish tenants were disproportionately likely to have fallen into rent arrears because of the under-occupation penalty. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The research showed that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8 out of the 20 local authorities that had the worst arrears problems were in Scotland.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in Clackmannanshire two-thirds of the tenants affected had fallen into arrears, which was second only to Barrow in Cumbria, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> three-quarters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> were in arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Scottish local authorities reported that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">40-50%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the tenants affecte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d in their area had fallen into arrears. Unfortunately Glasgow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which has the highest number of tenants affected in any Scottish local authority area and also the highest levels of urban deprivation,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">failed to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> respond to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FoI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">request</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion Scotla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd are concerned by the arrears levels uncovered by the TUC research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as they represent the position only some 4 months since the Under-Occupation Penalty’s introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">extremely concerned that a large proportion of the tenants who are falling into arr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ears will be disabled people.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It must be feared that the proportion of tenants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&amp; disabled people falling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> into arrears will only increase as time goes by and any financial resources that claimants initially had at the outset of the penalty being imposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">become stretched or entirely exhausted.  Moreover some tenants will have been eligible for Discretionary Housing Payments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(DHPs) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">during the first four months but these are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">usually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> restricted to a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">month maximum and so they too </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are likely to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fall into arre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ars </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">when their DHPs are withdrawn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled People &amp; the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Threat of Eviction:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scottish Government’s Analytical Services Division have estimated</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the likely consequences of the introduction of the Under-Occupation Penalty. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">They estimated that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8,000 o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f the households affected would move to smaller properties and thus manage to avoid the penalty whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">half of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e remainder (43,000)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would be able to maintain their rent payments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and around half would fall into arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of the half that fell into a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rrears they believed that a quarter (i.e. nearly 11,000 households) would eventually be evicted. Given that 79% of the households affected contain at least one disabled person that might mean 8,000+ disabled people being evicted and becoming homeless.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion Scotland believe that these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now look to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over-optimistic projection</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s given the levels of arrears in some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scottish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">already at or above this level after only 4 months. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£20 million in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">funding being made avai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by Scottish Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to Local Authorities to bolster DHP Budgets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have an impact in reducing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the rate at which tenants are falling into arrears and thus being evicted.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nevertheless Inclusion Scotland believes that disabled people will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> amongst those least able to continue to meet their rent payments.  This is because the Under-Occupation Penalty has not been introduced in a vacuum but in a context where other benefits paid to sick and disabled people are being cut. Thus the cumulative i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mpact of other welfare reforms will have an impact on their financial resilience and therefore their ability to meet increased rent payments.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">According to the Sheffield Hallam University research</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> approximately 100,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scots </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disabled people will be moved off Employment Support Allowance (ESA) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by 2015 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">either because they exhaust their entitlement to contributory ESA or because they are re-classified as fully fit for work after a Work Capability Assessment (WCA). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e planned 20% budget reduction which the DWP is planning to achieve there will also be significant numbers (thousands at least) of disabled people on the Mobility Components and Care elements of DLA who will have to lose entitlement to the PIP to make the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">necessary savings.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.7</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Using the DWP’s own projections, by 2018, IS estimates that over </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">80,000</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> working age disabled people in Scotland will lose either some or all of the</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mobility allowance that they would otherwise have been entitled to</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if DLA entitlement criteria had continued to be used</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">46,200</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will lose higher/enhanced rate mobility allowance</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">34,100 </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will lose standard/lower rate mobility allowance</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As one in three higher rate mobility component recipients currently use their benefit </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to lease Motability vehicles well over </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">15,000</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disabled people in Scotland also stand to lose their cars and scooters.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.8</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Care component:  </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition because of the introduction of PIP –</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">30,250</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fewer disabled people in Scotland will receive Standard Daily Living (PIP)/Middle Rate Care(DLA), and, </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">74,000</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disabled people in Scotland who would otherwise have been entitled to Lower Rate Care (DLA) will no longer receive it because it will no longer</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> exist.</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Conversely an additional </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">15,500</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more disabled people will qualify for the Enhanced Daily Living Element of PIP than would have qualified for the old Higher Rate Care of DLA. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">      </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However overall nearly </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">90,000</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fewer disabled peop</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le in Scotland</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will qualify for </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assistance with their care needs/daily living costs that they would otherwise have been entitled to under DLA eligibility criteria. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thus far, the DWP has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">refused to conduct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a Cumulative Impact  A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssessment due to what it argue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the difficulties in model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing ‘behaviour effects’. However, using the DWP’s own figures in relation to the benefits disabled people received, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have been able to calculate that working age disabled people who are 40+ will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disproportiona</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tely affected by reforms to Employment &amp; Support Allowance, the replacement of Disability Living Allowance by the Personal Independence Payment and the Under-Occupation Penalty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Thus - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PIP (2/3 of people on the soon to be defunct lower rate of care are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over 45); </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ESA (the majority of people who will lose entitlement to the means-tested PIP will be 40+, more likely to have savings and/or a partner in work); and,</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Bedroom </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tax:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">55</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the tenants affected are aged 45+</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very likely that there will be a significant overlap between these groups of disabled claimants (e.g. ESA and DLA Lower Rate Care recipients) as both groups have large cohorts of people with learning difficulties and/or mental health issues/cognitive impai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rments (e.g. autism spectrum disorder). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thus 40% of c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">laimants who have already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lost entitlement to Employment and Support Allowance have learning difficulties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/mental health issues whilst over 30% of those currently on DLA Lower Rate Care also have these i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mpairments.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.12</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Research carried out by Demos on behalf of Scope</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> confirms that a substantial proportion of disabled people will experience multiple cuts in their entitlement to benefits. The research suggests that across the UK 120,000 disabled people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will experience at least a triple loss of benefits by 2018 with 99,000 experiencing a quadruple cut. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The personal benefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">losses will range from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a minimum of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£6,300 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£23,461 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">per person by 2017.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Research by the Scottish Public Health Observatory</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> shows that 72,660 people were in receipt of three key benefits (Income Support/Pension Credit, Incapacity Benefit/Employment and Support Allowance/Severe Disablement Allowance, and Disability Living Allowance)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> affected by cuts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and 226,520 were in receipt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of at least two of the key benefits.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.14</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">      </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thus we think it safe to conclude that many of those losing ESA and/or other disability benefits (e.g. via the introduction of PIP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and changes to ESA entitlement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also be penalis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> under the Under-Occupation regulations.  This means that they will already or in the future suffer substantial losses to their household incomes making it more likely that they will be unable to maintain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rent payments and thus also more likely to ev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">entually be evicted.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23.25pt; text-indent:-23.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Exemptions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> to the Under Occupation Rule</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion Scotland believes that current exemptions to the Under Occupation rule are inconsistent with established case law, wider equality law and disabled people’s human rights. They are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> also being inconsistently applied by local authorities and Registered Social Landlords.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since the Court of Appeal judgment in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Gorry V Department of Work and Pensions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have received guidance from the DWP to allow an extra bedroom for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children who are unable to share because of their severe disabilities.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However no such exemption has been put in place for adult partners unable, or unwilling, to share a bed because of one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or both</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> severe impairments.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We believe that this failure to exempt couple’s unable to share a bed is inconsistent with established case law, with equalities law which states that disabled people should not be treated less favourably than non-disabled people  (as it could result in di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sabled people’s health and safety being jeopardised) and with disabled people’s right, under the Human Rights Act and Article 8 of the European Convention, to a ‘home and family life’.   </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.4     Inclusion Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believe that it is a totally unwarranted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> intrusion into the private lives of disabled people, and their partners, for the state to insist that they sleep in the same bed on pain of suffering a reduction to their housing benefit and that an exemption should be granted on these grounds forthwith.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion Scotland also believes that an exemption should exist for sick and disabled people who use one of their rooms to store equipment or other items associated with supporting them to live with their condition or impairment. For example a room u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sed to store a kidney dialysis machine is patently not being used as a bedroom and should not therefore be treated as one. </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A case (Lall v Westminster Council) on this very same  legal point was decided in favour of the claimant by a Lower Tier Tribunal ju</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dge. See here for details – </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/sep/26/bedroom-tax-westminster-council-defeat"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/sep/26/bedroom-tax-westminster-council-defeat</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e view the failure to provide such an exemption as jeopardising sick and disabled people’s health and ability to live independently. As only disabled people have an essential need for additional rooms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is not shared by non-disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that the Under-occupation penalty is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a breach of equality law which prohibits being treated differently on the grounds of disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and of Article 14 of the ECHR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This was also the view of a Lower Tier Tribunal judge in Glasgow in an as yet unreported </span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dec</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ision -</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> see here for the judge’</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s comments: </span><a href="http://govanlc.blogspot.co.uk/2013/10/european-convention-of-human-rights.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://govanlc.blogspot.co.uk/2013/10/european-convention-of-human-rights.html</span></a><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There have also been a number of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rulings in a Fife Lower Tier Tribunal on whether rooms can be treated as “bedrooms” for Under-occupation penalty purposes.  The judge in these cases ruled that rooms under 70 sq. feet in area could not be treated as bedrooms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for use by adults and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that exempt accommodation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where care and support was being provided by a Housing Association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, whether or not contracted to do so by a local authority, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">coul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d not be subjected to a penalty. See here for details – </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.insidehousing.co.uk/regulation/full-details-of-first-bedroom-tax-tribunal-rulings/6528701.article"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.insidehousing.co.uk/regulation/full-details-of-first-bedroom-tax-tribunal-rulings/6528701.article</span></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Discretionary Housing Payments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&amp; DLA/PIP Entitlement</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e DWP made significant additional amounts of funding available to local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to make Discretionary Housing Payments (DHPs) available to those affected by the Under Occupation penalty and other changes to Housing Benefit/Local Housing Allowance. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Guidance</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> issued by the DWP specifically recognized that disabled people were likely to be disproportionately affected by the penalty and that local authorities should therefore consider making DHPs where, for example, “additional” bedrooms were being used by partn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ers who could not share a bed with a disabled spouse.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However it appears that disabled people have been placed in a “Catch 22” situation in regards to being granted a DHP by local authorities. On the one hand they have to prove that they are a disable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d person, in which case the local authority may ask for proof of entitlement to DLA or PIP.  But on the other when they prove said entitlement they are then told that they are not eligible for a DHP because they have additional funding that they can draw o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n to pay the Under Occupation penalty, namely the very same DLA or PIP benefits payments!</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It should be pointed out that DLA is paid to disabled people to assist in meeting the additional costs associated with their disability. If it is already being us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed for that purpose then it should surely not be counted by local authorities as disposable income available to the disabled person to meet the Under Occupation penalty. Yet that is exactly what has been happening.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There does not seem to be a consis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tent approach across local authorities to a claimant having entitlement to DLA/PIP and their subsequent application for a DHP. The result is that severely impaired people having difficulty in paying their rent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are being denied support from the very funds s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">et aside for that purpose.  This will inevitably result in severe financial pressure on households containing a disabled person who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">affected by the ‘Bedroom Tax’, the very likely accumulation of rent arrears and the potential for, and reality, of evict</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ions at some stage.   Needless to say the emotional stress that will be suffered by individuals and families will also be severe and has already led to incidents of suicide and self-harm.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inclusion Scotland believe that in taking DLA into account as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disposable income for DHP purposes that local authorities are discriminating against disabled people as non-disabled people do not have access to DLA/PIP and are thus more likely to qualify for DHPs. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This same legal argument was advanced by a disable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d claimant in Glasgow and we note that the local authority then reviewed their DHP decision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (see here for details - </span><a href="http://disabilityrightsuk.org/news/2013/june/discretionary-housing-payment-includes-dla"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://disabilityrightsuk.org/news/2013</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">/june/discretionary-housing-payment-includes-dla</span></a><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However it is massively unfair that other disabled people within the same local authority area (and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also in other authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) may still be being denied DHPs on the grounds that they are receiving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DLA/PIP as no case law precedent was established that DLA should not be taken into account. This should be addressed by making DWP Guidance much more specific in calling for DLA/PIP payments to be disregarded by local authorities when considering whether t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o award DHPs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">3 October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Impact of Planned Housing Benefit Changes in Scotland: The Number of Disabled Households Affected By The Under-Occupancy Penalty, Scottish Government, Feb 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Updated Evidence On The Number Of Households Affected By The Housing Benefit Under Occupatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n Penalty, Scottish Government, June 2013</span></p><h1 style="margin:5pt 0pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">“Bedroom tax has pushed one in three council tenants into arrears”,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> TUC Press Release, 19/9/13. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">See: http://www.tuc.org.uk/social/tuc-22608-f0.cfm </span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Built-Environment/Housing/supply-demand/chma/Benefitchanges/BenefitChangesUnderOccupancy"><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">Reducing the Housing Benefit of Households of Working Age in Social Housing</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">Under-Occupying a Property, Scottish Governm</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">ent, Analytical Services, Dec. 2012</span><span style="color:#0d0d0d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">&#xa0;</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn5"></a><a href="#_ednref5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">Incapacity Benefit Reform: the local, regional and national impact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Beatty &amp; Fothergill, Sheffield Hallam University, 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn6"></a><a href="#_ednref6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Destination Unknown April 2013, Demos, April 2013 See here: </span><a href="http://www.demos.co.uk/blog/destinationunknownapril2013"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.demos.co.uk/blog/destinationunknownapril2013</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_edn7"></a><a href="#_ednref7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">Making a bad situation worse? The impact of welfare reform and the economic recession on health and health inequalities in Scotland (baseline report), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">Gerry McCartney et al on behalf of the Scottish Public Health Observatory, October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn8"></a><a href="#_ednref8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Discretionary Housing Payments Guidance Manual; Including Loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l Authority Good Practice Guide, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DWP, April 2013</span></p></body></html>